1
00:00:01,921 --> 00:00:30,696
namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:31,603 --> 00:00:59,856
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one Karma To start at the beginning to understand the Buddha's way of looking at what happens in the universe

3
00:01:00,847 --> 00:01:11,060
he talks about the sort of fundamental law, which is known as the Pachayatah, the law of this and that, Idda Pachayatah, the law of this and that.

4
00:01:12,081 --> 00:01:13,623
You can't get simpler than that.

5
00:01:14,864 --> 00:01:20,430
So the law states, as far as he's concerned, because this happened in the past, this is happening now.

6
00:01:21,230 --> 00:01:24,594
Because this hasn't happened in the past, this doesn't happen now.

7
00:01:26,734 --> 00:01:31,021
Because this is happening in the present, that is also happening in the present.

8
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:35,507
And because that isn't happening in the present, that does not also happen in the present.

9
00:01:38,111 --> 00:01:38,751
Need I explain?

10
00:01:41,115 --> 00:01:50,108
So the first one is concerned with karma in the terms of cause and effect, temporal cause and effect, passing through time.

11
00:01:51,331 --> 00:01:54,295
So you made a decision to visit a dentist and there you are.

12
00:01:55,760 --> 00:01:57,841
Cause and effect, passing through time.

13
00:01:59,224 --> 00:02:07,534
However, if it were just that, if it were just that the present moment were conditioned by the past, then you're into predestination, aren't you?

14
00:02:07,793 --> 00:02:10,578
You're into a set pattern.

15
00:02:14,421 --> 00:02:18,127
It would be hard to see how you could get creativity.

16
00:02:20,969 --> 00:02:23,353
Perhaps the universe would just keep repeating itself.

17
00:02:27,282 --> 00:02:42,377
If things only happen because things arise in the now unconnected with the past then you're looking at a sort of chaos, aren't you?

18
00:02:49,024 --> 00:02:56,951
If we can put those two concepts together then we have the Buddha's understanding of what's happening in the universe.

19
00:02:58,012 --> 00:03:04,139
And in a sense, it approximates, as far as I understand, the modern theory of chaos.

20
00:03:06,020 --> 00:03:22,938
So, having read that book, and therefore, of course, presenting myself as an expert, it says in one example that the butterfly wing, the flap of a butterfly wing in Australia, ends up as a hurricane bursting its way through the United States.

21
00:03:25,635 --> 00:03:38,435
So, in the past we can see the butterfly wing, but conditions around it produce the turbulence, conditions around that produce further turbulence, and before you know it, you have a hurricane or a tornado.

22
00:03:41,098 --> 00:03:55,338
So, the law states that something is coming into the present and meeting other things coming from different pasts in the present, and hence you have a new creative situation.

23
00:03:57,022 --> 00:03:58,024
And the opposite is true.

24
00:03:58,185 --> 00:04:00,967
If something doesn't arise, something else happens.

25
00:04:02,030 --> 00:04:05,234
So the sun comes up and it's a lovely summer and the harvest is great.

26
00:04:05,615 --> 00:04:08,718
And the workers are out there and the money's earned and everybody's happy.

27
00:04:10,421 --> 00:04:16,310
The sunshine fails to come, the harvest doesn't happen, people don't eat, and there's famine.

28
00:04:19,795 --> 00:04:21,997
Yeah?

29
00:04:22,017 --> 00:04:26,524
All of us are here in this room having made decisions in the past, completely separate from each other.

30
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:28,201
And here we are.

31
00:04:30,505 --> 00:04:31,327
Oh, happy gathering.

32
00:04:36,375 --> 00:04:40,903
So that's the law of iddha-pacchayatā.

33
00:04:41,185 --> 00:04:52,545
That's what the Buddha saw as basically happening at that level.

34
00:04:56,423 --> 00:05:04,134
When it comes to something that happens to human beings, so that's a physical law, you see, the law of physics, you might say.

35
00:05:04,153 --> 00:05:12,545
When it comes to something that happens to human beings, it's fairly easy to accept the law of karma so long as we can see some sort of justice.

36
00:05:14,988 --> 00:05:18,194
So they work hard and you get the money and you own a nice house.

37
00:05:18,535 --> 00:05:19,596
That's good karma.

38
00:05:21,161 --> 00:05:24,927
You have a good life, but then unfortunately you get a bad illness.

39
00:05:24,947 --> 00:05:26,288
That's bad karma.

40
00:05:26,949 --> 00:05:27,930
But that's the way it is.

41
00:05:29,392 --> 00:05:33,096
When something outlandish happens, then it's difficult.

42
00:05:35,259 --> 00:05:37,403
So the murder of two little innocent girls.

43
00:05:39,685 --> 00:05:41,168
Hollywell's Jessica Chapman.

44
00:05:43,029 --> 00:05:45,814
An earthquake in Turkey, or the one in Japan.

45
00:05:45,853 --> 00:05:48,317
Thousands of people just crushed.

46
00:05:48,904 --> 00:05:51,687
Or indeed, the people in the Twin Towers.

47
00:05:52,850 --> 00:06:00,077
So when we come across a real disaster which doesn't make sense, then this idea of human justice comes in.

48
00:06:02,120 --> 00:06:03,382
Something has to be just.

49
00:06:05,584 --> 00:06:09,028
Now justice belongs to a system of punishment and reward.

50
00:06:10,670 --> 00:06:14,254
So in the 18th century it was perfectly just to hang somebody for stealing a sheep.

51
00:06:18,470 --> 00:06:21,173
Now you can commit mass murder and you go to jail.

52
00:06:23,194 --> 00:06:25,055
I'm not suggesting that that's not what should happen.

53
00:06:26,478 --> 00:06:34,144
It's just that, obviously, when we come to justice, reward and punishment, it's entirely dependent on what human beings think is justice.

54
00:06:36,226 --> 00:06:37,949
Remember the old Gilbert and Sullivan, you see?

55
00:06:38,709 --> 00:06:39,449
And Ricardo, isn't it?

56
00:06:39,490 --> 00:06:40,750
Let the punishment fit the crime.

57
00:06:44,814 --> 00:06:47,817
For his innocent merriment, that was the emperor, wasn't it?

58
00:06:52,591 --> 00:06:55,654
So, that isn't the law of karma.

59
00:06:55,915 --> 00:07:06,166
The law of karma is really stating that in fact all this business about reward and punishment is something that we produce for ourselves.

60
00:07:06,687 --> 00:07:07,829
It's our personal karma.

61
00:07:08,490 --> 00:07:12,735
If we decide to punish somebody, then we're laying on that person extra suffering.

62
00:07:14,016 --> 00:07:18,901
Because whatever we do, there's got to be some sort of consequence.

63
00:07:19,237 --> 00:07:20,678
That's the better word for karma.

64
00:07:20,879 --> 00:07:21,420
Consequence.

65
00:07:21,940 --> 00:07:23,704
You do something and there's a consequence.

66
00:07:23,923 --> 00:07:24,564
There's an effect.

67
00:07:30,874 --> 00:07:41,348
However, we are not in charge of the process that happens to an action once we've performed it.

68
00:07:41,369 --> 00:07:42,190
That's the problem.

69
00:07:43,992 --> 00:07:47,218
That butterfly never meant to do any harm.

70
00:07:49,122 --> 00:07:52,288
But he was put in jail for years for calling that article.

71
00:07:53,911 --> 00:07:54,151
See?

72
00:07:56,836 --> 00:08:01,745
There was a case here in Totnes, I was told, of a charity group that collected clothes.

73
00:08:02,264 --> 00:08:03,648
Clothes for the poor in Africa.

74
00:08:05,211 --> 00:08:06,713
A very compassionate, loving idea.

75
00:08:07,274 --> 00:08:09,879
So they collected all these clothes and they all went to Africa.

76
00:08:10,620 --> 00:08:12,142
And they put all the tailors out of work.

77
00:08:14,197 --> 00:08:19,786
So that wonderful compassionate act ended up with massive suffering for a lot of people.

78
00:08:21,168 --> 00:08:25,375
Just because you do something out of the goodness of your heart doesn't mean that everybody's going to be happy with it.

79
00:08:27,920 --> 00:08:29,762
So the world is a very complicated place.

80
00:08:33,188 --> 00:08:34,029
Now,

81
00:08:34,886 --> 00:08:50,431
If we say that karma is much more to do with action and its product, and I'm using here karma as we use it in the vernacular, in the ordinary sense of something that's resulted, that's not its actual proper use.

82
00:08:50,510 --> 00:08:51,993
Its proper use is just action.

83
00:08:53,475 --> 00:08:57,041
The result is, the proper word for that is viparka.

84
00:08:58,123 --> 00:09:01,467
But just using it as we normally use it, you know, bad karma, good karma.

85
00:09:03,254 --> 00:09:11,864
we can see that everything that happens to us is not our personal responsibility.

86
00:09:11,884 --> 00:09:16,649
So the law of karma is only one of five laws that the Buddha taught.

87
00:09:17,610 --> 00:09:31,927
Now, strictly speaking, I'm not absolutely sure that this was something he taught directly, because I can't remember, or whether it's something which was extrapolated from the text by later commentaries.

88
00:09:33,780 --> 00:09:50,138
But these five laws are, shall we say, a compendium of laws which hopefully explain why things happen to us as individuals, to us as we experience ourselves as individual human beings.

89
00:09:51,418 --> 00:09:58,826
So the first one is known as the law of heat, utu, and it actually refers to what these days we would call physics, chemistry.

90
00:10:01,692 --> 00:10:04,535
Now, there are things that happen in that world which have nothing to do with us, is it?

91
00:10:05,356 --> 00:10:06,057
We're an earthquake.

92
00:10:06,899 --> 00:10:15,190
You can't say that you were crushed in an earthquake because in a past life you stood on a thousand ants.

93
00:10:15,210 --> 00:10:26,264
The connection between all those ants that you very cruelly stood on in that past life and the movement of the earth with its tectonic plates is difficult to see.

94
00:10:29,434 --> 00:10:31,980
Did all those ants go down there and push those plates?

95
00:10:33,663 --> 00:10:34,945
It gets ridiculous.

96
00:10:35,426 --> 00:10:43,419
You can't measure what happens to you from the outside world as being your personal karma.

97
00:10:43,440 --> 00:10:48,067
In fact, it seems a little arrogant.

98
00:10:48,087 --> 00:10:53,518
The second law is bija, and it translates as seed, and it equates to our genetics.

99
00:10:55,708 --> 00:11:00,235
So now we know the physical structure we have is the product of history.

100
00:11:00,254 --> 00:11:09,826
I mean, if you're born with a congenital disease, what can you do?

101
00:11:09,866 --> 00:11:16,215
It's come up to you from past generations.

102
00:11:16,235 --> 00:11:25,226
If, as we had that awful disaster in the 60s, I think it was, when thalidomide was produced as a help for women in pregnancy.

103
00:11:25,797 --> 00:11:27,860
and children were born without limbs.

104
00:11:31,466 --> 00:11:33,828
It's not a personal karma.

105
00:11:38,996 --> 00:11:46,489
So when it comes to anything to do with genetics, this body has to be accepted as a product of past generations.

106
00:11:47,667 --> 00:11:52,123
Now, there is a little side comment to make there.

107
00:11:52,884 --> 00:11:56,538
Because remembering Buddhas in the mind and the body are intimately connected.

108
00:11:57,822 --> 00:11:59,347
Milk in water, the Buddha says.

109
00:12:00,745 --> 00:12:10,019
And we can see that when we produce in ourselves unwholesome states, it has an effect on the body.

110
00:12:10,980 --> 00:12:15,746
Very simply, we know that anger hurts the heart, we know that anxiety gives you bad indigestion.

111
00:12:15,947 --> 00:12:20,394
On that level, it's pretty obvious.

112
00:12:21,254 --> 00:12:26,482
But there's also suggestions that it can also change a very genetic structure.

113
00:12:26,563 --> 00:12:33,394
so that the gene patterns change, or fault, so that you come up with a fault line in a genetic pattern.

114
00:12:34,115 --> 00:12:34,897
And this carries on.

115
00:12:35,658 --> 00:12:37,320
This carries on as a history.

116
00:12:40,905 --> 00:12:42,148
But it could also be other things.

117
00:12:42,769 --> 00:12:48,116
It could be all the radioactive pollution that we've got.

118
00:12:48,248 --> 00:13:01,659
All these poor animals up in the Arctic, you know, these polar bears being born with all sorts of peculiarities because of this distortion in the genetic code through this pollution up there.

119
00:13:03,701 --> 00:13:05,182
So we can't say that they deserve that.

120
00:13:08,485 --> 00:13:12,490
So that's Bija, that's the business about genetics.

121
00:13:12,509 --> 00:13:16,212
So the body we end up in, well, that's just it, you know, you've got to do your best, you know.

122
00:13:21,052 --> 00:13:27,243
Not part of our personal karma.

123
00:13:27,263 --> 00:13:30,827
The third one is citta, which means mind.

124
00:13:31,509 --> 00:13:37,238
Now, strictly speaking in the commentaries, it refers to the way the mind works, what we would call psychology.

125
00:13:37,759 --> 00:13:42,105
But I don't think you can abstract that from the effects of society on the mind.

126
00:13:42,605 --> 00:13:44,929
So, through mind, you have to include culture.

127
00:13:46,673 --> 00:13:48,816
You have to include the language you speak.

128
00:13:49,522 --> 00:14:01,523
which orders your thoughts, gives you certain patterns of thinking which connects you with your civilization and on a very personal level connects you with the culture of your own family.

129
00:14:02,870 --> 00:14:20,677
So your mind is that whole business of what we've constructed within ourselves, made within ourselves, our emotional and thought life, that we've made within ourselves, but obviously in communion, in communication with the situation that we've found ourselves.

130
00:14:22,860 --> 00:14:25,062
Now we're not in charge of that situation, are we?

131
00:14:26,342 --> 00:14:40,245
If you happen to be born destitute in a sort of family which is in the middle of Africa or India, it's a very different life, isn't it, from somebody who's born, say, in the West, generally speaking.

132
00:14:40,485 --> 00:14:41,748
Not to say there are not poor people here.

133
00:14:45,734 --> 00:14:47,076
But you've no control over that.

134
00:14:47,316 --> 00:14:49,580
That's what we're working with.

135
00:14:49,600 --> 00:14:53,346
That's the stuff that we've got to work with.

136
00:14:57,595 --> 00:15:01,902
So that's the mind, citta, in its general form.

137
00:15:02,342 --> 00:15:05,528
Now the next one is karma, and I'll leave that for a moment.

138
00:15:05,548 --> 00:15:09,073
The last one is dhamma, and that's all the laws, the spiritual laws.

139
00:15:10,014 --> 00:15:12,940
So the Four Noble Truths, the Eightfold Path, all that sort of stuff.

140
00:15:12,960 --> 00:15:23,096
So they belong to another section in Buddhist understanding, which are laws which, if you follow, have certain effects.

141
00:15:24,544 --> 00:15:30,250
So there's your five laws and one of them is karma.

142
00:15:30,269 --> 00:15:36,495
Now karma is specifically to do with our intentions.

143
00:15:38,397 --> 00:15:39,818
As the Buddha says, it's quite clear.

144
00:15:41,340 --> 00:15:49,667
Chaitanya, aham chaitanya, kama vandami bhikkhu.

145
00:15:49,687 --> 00:15:52,509
I call your will kama.

146
00:15:53,096 --> 00:15:55,980
Now, the Buddha here is using karma to mean action.

147
00:15:56,580 --> 00:15:56,921
Action.

148
00:15:58,722 --> 00:16:02,385
And the will is what empowers something to produce an action.

149
00:16:03,386 --> 00:16:04,687
And there are three actions.

150
00:16:05,048 --> 00:16:07,951
Actions of thought, actions of speech, and actions of body.

151
00:16:10,453 --> 00:16:14,798
And what you do is you are empowering, you are empowering an intention.

152
00:16:15,980 --> 00:16:20,403
So this karma, in terms of why we suffer,

153
00:16:21,058 --> 00:16:23,581
is contained in the wheel of dependent origination.

154
00:16:29,049 --> 00:16:32,615
In that wheel, what you have is the contact with the world.

155
00:16:34,256 --> 00:16:35,658
For those of you who know it, the pasta.

156
00:16:35,778 --> 00:16:37,500
That's the contact we have with the world.

157
00:16:38,942 --> 00:16:43,870
From that, we have an internal response, which we call feeling.

158
00:16:44,591 --> 00:16:46,273
Pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

159
00:16:47,856 --> 00:16:55,344
And that's our reaction, response to the world as it comes to us.

160
00:16:55,403 --> 00:16:59,729
Whether it be a television set, somebody speaking to us, a meditation room, it doesn't matter.

161
00:17:00,249 --> 00:17:05,354
It arises in the heart a certain response, a certain feeling.

162
00:17:05,374 --> 00:17:13,442
And we react to that coming from a self of either indulging what is pleasant or pushing away what is unpleasant.

163
00:17:13,607 --> 00:17:15,411
We're always caught up in that game.

164
00:17:15,530 --> 00:17:20,018
The self really doesn't have an option apart from just simply ignoring something.

165
00:17:22,162 --> 00:17:23,523
It's always caught up in the game.

166
00:17:24,826 --> 00:17:25,968
You've only got to watch yourself.

167
00:17:26,229 --> 00:17:29,693
The mind is always moving from, oh that's nice, oh no, I don't want that.

168
00:17:29,713 --> 00:17:31,396
It's always shifting.

169
00:17:34,059 --> 00:17:44,501
As soon as you've decided on something that you want, as soon as you've decided that you like something or dislike something, then you have that reaction of wanting, not wanting.

170
00:17:44,721 --> 00:17:45,723
And that's your tanha.

171
00:17:46,946 --> 00:17:47,669
That's your desire.

172
00:17:48,329 --> 00:17:52,638
And as soon as that desire has arisen, there's an identification with the desire.

173
00:17:53,681 --> 00:17:54,583
I want.

174
00:17:55,306 --> 00:17:57,208
In our language, the I comes first.

175
00:17:57,449 --> 00:17:57,868
I want.

176
00:17:58,289 --> 00:18:00,752
But in Buddhist psychology, it's the other way around.

177
00:18:00,813 --> 00:18:01,212
Want I.

178
00:18:02,413 --> 00:18:03,776
There's a grasping onto it.

179
00:18:03,895 --> 00:18:05,238
That's why it's called Upadan.

180
00:18:05,258 --> 00:18:06,199
It's grasping onto it.

181
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:11,125
And as soon as you've done that, that desire is empowered.

182
00:18:11,605 --> 00:18:12,086
Bhava.

183
00:18:12,445 --> 00:18:14,308
And Bhava translates as becoming.

184
00:18:15,190 --> 00:18:15,710
Becoming.

185
00:18:16,211 --> 00:18:21,297
So becoming and karma and will are all the same thing.

186
00:18:23,740 --> 00:18:26,925
Now, when you do that, two things are happening.

187
00:18:27,926 --> 00:18:37,483
First of all, there's an action which goes out into the world over which now we can see we have very little control.

188
00:18:37,523 --> 00:18:48,903
Whether I set up a good action of sending old clothes to Africa or a bad action of mugging some sweet old person on the street,

189
00:18:49,406 --> 00:18:52,351
After that, it's that butterfly wing.

190
00:18:52,550 --> 00:18:53,873
I don't know where it's going to go.

191
00:18:53,893 --> 00:18:56,355
I might get away with it.

192
00:18:57,778 --> 00:18:58,980
I might get away with this mugging.

193
00:19:01,864 --> 00:19:05,648
And it so happens the person has one million pounds in their pocket.

194
00:19:05,669 --> 00:19:06,169
It's pretty good.

195
00:19:09,253 --> 00:19:16,343
On the other hand, I might be taken to court by all these tailors in Africa and sued for ruining their jobs.

196
00:19:17,470 --> 00:19:19,132
Next time you send clothes, send us a wage.

197
00:19:22,214 --> 00:19:22,535
See?

198
00:19:22,555 --> 00:19:23,256
So you don't know.

199
00:19:23,276 --> 00:19:28,020
Now, how much responsibility can we take for that?

200
00:19:30,182 --> 00:19:32,045
Because you've put it into the pot.

201
00:19:32,065 --> 00:19:33,307
Other people are going to grasp it.

202
00:19:33,326 --> 00:19:34,647
The environment is going to grasp it.

203
00:19:37,451 --> 00:19:41,976
Surely the only responsibility we can take is for our initial intention.

204
00:19:43,728 --> 00:19:48,375
As soon as other people join in, as soon as the environment takes hold of it, that's it.

205
00:19:51,020 --> 00:19:55,848
So we can't blame ourselves or find ourselves feeling guilty for things over which we've no control.

206
00:19:56,971 --> 00:20:03,541
But we can over our particular intention, the initial intention we had.

207
00:20:05,699 --> 00:20:14,230
So, having made this decision, there's an action which goes out in the world over which we've got very little control and which will come back to us in some way.

208
00:20:14,790 --> 00:20:15,811
Come back to us in some way.

209
00:20:16,834 --> 00:20:24,243
So it may be, for instance, that I'm here preparing this wonderful charity and all these people are really getting cheesed off about it.

210
00:20:24,903 --> 00:20:27,847
And I go out there thinking what a wonderful thing it is that I've done.

211
00:20:28,189 --> 00:20:29,911
And I land and somebody shoots me in the head.

212
00:20:32,855 --> 00:20:32,954
Yeah.

213
00:20:34,538 --> 00:20:41,924
somebody don't like me am I responsible for that?

214
00:20:44,327 --> 00:21:01,203
now what is happening on the outside something else is happening on the inside so that action, that act of will is now producing a circumstance within my own mind

215
00:21:01,538 --> 00:21:08,816
So as soon as I intend something, I'm setting up a specific conditioning within my mind, within my heart.

216
00:21:09,837 --> 00:21:17,978
So if I intend something compassionate, I am producing a conditioning in myself to produce a compassionate heart.

217
00:21:18,987 --> 00:21:31,864
If I set up one intention which I empower, even in my thought, remember, it doesn't have to be speech or action, just in my thought, and I empower a cruel thought, I set up a conditioning for cruelty.

218
00:21:37,111 --> 00:21:41,135
Now, you can see that we have two things here, two things happening.

219
00:21:41,636 --> 00:21:45,821
We have the outside world, over which I have little control,

220
00:21:46,460 --> 00:21:49,905
and the inside world over which I have total control.

221
00:21:52,210 --> 00:21:53,031
There's a real split.

222
00:21:56,196 --> 00:22:03,631
It's myself who's produced all these emotions, all this restlessness and depression and guilt.

223
00:22:03,651 --> 00:22:06,536
But I've also produced joy, compassion, peace.

224
00:22:07,698 --> 00:22:10,542
My inner environment is my own little domain.

225
00:22:14,319 --> 00:22:19,945
I didn't know this as a kid, else I wouldn't have done a lot of things that I did do.

226
00:22:19,965 --> 00:22:22,388
But unfortunately, I'm stuck with what I've got.

227
00:22:23,169 --> 00:22:24,871
That's my ignorance, that's myself.

228
00:22:26,032 --> 00:22:30,998
That's me looking at the world as a place where I can be perfectly happy.

229
00:22:31,258 --> 00:22:33,901
Trying to manipulate the world so that I can be happy in it.

230
00:22:36,022 --> 00:22:44,192
But I'm also constantly creating this environment within myself.

231
00:22:46,011 --> 00:23:01,961
so we can see that when something happens to us from the outside we may be only connected to it by way of being there

232
00:23:02,313 --> 00:23:04,977
I mean, all those people in the towers, they were just there.

233
00:23:05,076 --> 00:23:06,159
Some of them were just there.

234
00:23:06,519 --> 00:23:12,209
But somehow they were connected because of what they did, because of their job and all that.

235
00:23:12,229 --> 00:23:15,855
They were connected with all this business that's going on at this political level.

236
00:23:16,496 --> 00:23:24,067
But some of them were there just as tourists.

237
00:23:25,178 --> 00:23:27,280
So now what is their karma?

238
00:23:28,001 --> 00:23:36,193
In the sense of what is it that they've suffered as a consequence of something in the past?

239
00:23:36,854 --> 00:23:40,058
Or what is it that they're suffering as personal karma?

240
00:23:41,780 --> 00:23:46,807
You see, if we say it was the crushing towers then we've got a lot of explaining to do.

241
00:23:49,412 --> 00:23:52,856
If we say it was their fear or their lack of fear

242
00:23:55,384 --> 00:24:01,493
then that's them, isn't it?

243
00:24:01,513 --> 00:24:17,538
So, in that situation, as in all situations of great stress, be it a war, be it an earthquake, or be it something as terrible as that, there's always this individual who is in that situation, in their own little world.

244
00:24:19,800 --> 00:24:21,442
We see it as an objective thing.

245
00:24:21,502 --> 00:24:23,906
We see the wall, we see the towers collapse.

246
00:24:24,982 --> 00:24:28,737
But what the person there is experiencing is only what they're experiencing.

247
00:24:29,038 --> 00:24:31,105
And that's their suffering or non-suffering.

248
00:24:32,752 --> 00:24:33,896
And that's their karma.

249
00:24:43,157 --> 00:24:54,932
So there will have been somebody in that tower who will not have felt afraid and who will have felt a need for compassion to help people who were in dire straits.

250
00:24:56,354 --> 00:24:58,715
There will have been those who would have been killed outright.

251
00:24:58,777 --> 00:25:00,679
There wouldn't have been perhaps any feeling at all.

252
00:25:02,340 --> 00:25:06,786
There would have been those who died in abject fear, abject fear, in terror.

253
00:25:10,494 --> 00:25:39,387
but that's them, that's their particular mental state produced by their own internal karma and what we're trying to do in our meditation is to purify the heart completely and to take away that initial mistake that we've made it's a mistake of believing that this is what we are this body, mind and heart psychophysical organism

254
00:25:40,651 --> 00:25:40,830
See?

255
00:25:41,172 --> 00:25:42,532
I like that phrase.

256
00:25:42,553 --> 00:25:43,654
Psychophysical organism.

257
00:25:44,655 --> 00:25:48,200
It's breaking through the delusion that that's what we are.

258
00:25:49,041 --> 00:25:49,342
You see?

259
00:25:49,362 --> 00:25:53,067
And if that's not what we are, how can it ever cause us suffering?

260
00:26:04,161 --> 00:26:07,704
So if we look at something like innocence, like these two little girls...

261
00:26:09,170 --> 00:26:13,714
Well, we know that there are many children these days who are in dire straits.

262
00:26:15,896 --> 00:26:26,327
And I'm just bringing back to memory now that the Moors murder, where they even taped the screams and stuff of the kids that they were torturing.

263
00:26:27,308 --> 00:26:30,011
They were on tape, for heaven's sake.

264
00:26:30,031 --> 00:26:34,317
So that for us, of course, is very difficult for us to bear.

265
00:26:34,499 --> 00:26:36,342
Because of the innocence of it, you know.

266
00:26:37,282 --> 00:26:40,307
Even if it's somebody who isn't so innocent, it's difficult to bear.

267
00:26:40,607 --> 00:26:44,795
But when it's somebody, when it's a child, it's extra specially difficult to bear.

268
00:26:44,855 --> 00:26:51,124
So what then would be the understanding of karma for those children?

269
00:26:53,045 --> 00:27:09,555
Well, for some reason, conditions outside them, you see, this man, who knows how he came to be in that state of mind to commit that act, suddenly chooses them, you see.

270
00:27:11,638 --> 00:27:12,400
Lots of children.

271
00:27:12,820 --> 00:27:13,561
Why choose them?

272
00:27:14,904 --> 00:27:16,166
Was it opportunism?

273
00:27:17,007 --> 00:27:45,646
was it the fact that he was that it just happened that they were there and therefore he was suddenly taken by this obsession see who knows was it planned had he planned it before had he had some sort of special relationship with them who knows it may come out in court but for those children that whole time now has produced in them one can only presume this huge conditioning of absolute terror

274
00:27:46,285 --> 00:27:48,227
real hell, a real hell state.

275
00:27:48,467 --> 00:27:50,690
One can only presume that, at worst.

276
00:27:52,571 --> 00:28:02,142
So now what happens is, in Buddhist understanding, is that this is something they will have to sort out in future lifetimes.

277
00:28:05,865 --> 00:28:14,115
So this fear, remember, has not been caused, and this is what you really have to grasp, this has not been caused by that man.

278
00:28:16,541 --> 00:28:44,540
nobody can cause us psychological pain that fear has been produced by their fundamental delusion the same delusion that we have that I am this body I am what I appear to be now

279
00:28:45,736 --> 00:29:12,367
what happens in Buddhist understanding is that through the process of rebirth there is a working out of that and everything that was unwholesome in that mind is eventually turned into its opposite so the amount of fear that we have in us will produce

280
00:29:13,089 --> 00:29:15,733
the equal amount of courage once it's turned.

281
00:29:18,238 --> 00:29:23,025
The cruelty that we have in us will produce an equal amount of compassion.

282
00:29:26,810 --> 00:29:30,856
Because all it is, is an energy force.

283
00:29:30,876 --> 00:29:34,001
All the hate we have will turn into love.

284
00:29:38,875 --> 00:29:52,894
But more than that, because as this transformation takes place, we can then continue to develop those qualities of joy, peace, love and compassion infinitely.

285
00:29:54,538 --> 00:29:56,441
Well, better word, indefinitely.

286
00:29:57,501 --> 00:29:59,144
Infinitely takes us into metaphysics.

287
00:30:00,246 --> 00:30:00,967
Indefinitely.

288
00:30:02,950 --> 00:30:04,932
Indefinitely in two ways.

289
00:30:05,065 --> 00:30:34,599
horizontally in the sense that since there are a limitable number of beings we can extend those qualities indefinitely that way and vertically in the sense that there is no end to the depth of love, compassion, joy and peace we can feel so even though these two children have had to suffer have had to go through an experience

290
00:30:35,203 --> 00:30:55,913
which has produced in them because of their delusion an awful and dreadful state of mind in the fullness of time they will work it out and they will gain the benefit of that working out so nothing is wasted

291
00:30:58,525 --> 00:31:02,192
Nothing we suffer is for nothingness.

292
00:31:02,952 --> 00:31:06,058
It always will produce something beautiful in the end.

293
00:31:08,202 --> 00:31:18,863
Now, the universe, as far as our consciousnesses are concerned, is so manufactured that we don't have a choice but to become enlightened.

294
00:31:21,272 --> 00:31:22,094
You don't have a choice.

295
00:31:23,075 --> 00:31:33,469
Only once in Buddhist history was there ever the dastardly theory that there were some people who would always be in samsara.

296
00:31:34,789 --> 00:31:35,411
Onward going.

297
00:31:36,211 --> 00:31:37,773
They were called the Ichikantas.

298
00:31:38,095 --> 00:31:39,957
Those who would go on forever.

299
00:31:42,400 --> 00:31:46,285
Because it was understood that there were some people who were just too thick.

300
00:31:49,116 --> 00:32:00,796
This awful doctrine remained only in a very small sect in Mahayana for a very short time and was banished.

301
00:32:03,240 --> 00:32:10,972
And the reason is that the self is continuously trying to find happiness in this world.

302
00:32:12,606 --> 00:32:13,849
It only has two ways.

303
00:32:14,852 --> 00:32:21,345
It either must try to build up a very pleasurable situation, or it must run away from what is unpleasurable.

304
00:32:22,165 --> 00:32:24,912
So, the image is the base of a triangle.

305
00:32:25,803 --> 00:32:33,451
It's always running towards pleasure, or it's always running away from hatred, away from painfulness.

306
00:32:34,173 --> 00:32:35,914
It's always running up and down this base.

307
00:32:36,316 --> 00:32:38,238
And that's what you're observing when you meditate.

308
00:32:38,357 --> 00:32:39,660
You're observing, this is dukkha.

309
00:32:40,099 --> 00:32:45,487
This is what the Buddha is talking about when he says, suffering, unsatisfactoriness.

310
00:32:45,507 --> 00:32:55,117
Every time we hit the wall of pleasure, when the pleasure doesn't arise, when the pleasure we depended upon disappears, suffering arises.

311
00:32:56,531 --> 00:33:02,179
Every time aversion arises, every time something horrible arises, we run away from it, but it chases us.

312
00:33:04,382 --> 00:33:06,505
You can't get away from your internal pain.

313
00:33:06,924 --> 00:33:08,007
You might think you're doing it.

314
00:33:08,446 --> 00:33:10,369
You can take drugs if you want, but it's still there.

315
00:33:12,352 --> 00:33:19,080
So, this game, the Buddha says, at some point, this suffering awakens a person.

316
00:33:19,421 --> 00:33:22,625
And it awakens the person to find the end of suffering.

317
00:33:23,326 --> 00:33:24,426
And this is his own life.

318
00:33:24,748 --> 00:33:24,867
Right?

319
00:33:25,590 --> 00:33:32,438
There he is, having a good time, and he comes across a very sick person, a very old person, and a corpse.

320
00:33:32,597 --> 00:33:33,338
You know the story.

321
00:33:33,818 --> 00:33:35,259
And each time he says, what is this?

322
00:33:35,279 --> 00:33:36,682
Because he's never seen anything like this before.

323
00:33:37,563 --> 00:33:40,365
And when they tell him he's a human being, his next question is crucial.

324
00:33:40,846 --> 00:33:41,626
Does it happen to me?

325
00:33:43,949 --> 00:33:52,257
When that broke into his consciousness that he could grow old, sick, and die, he had what we would call a nervous breakdown.

326
00:33:53,586 --> 00:33:56,131
An existential identity crisis.

327
00:33:57,333 --> 00:33:59,836
And it shot him out in search of the end of suffering.

328
00:34:02,200 --> 00:34:03,040
And he found it, you see.

329
00:34:03,461 --> 00:34:06,165
Now, that's exactly what is happening to us.

330
00:34:19,686 --> 00:34:21,188
So I think that's it, really.

331
00:34:22,248 --> 00:34:23,391
I think I've done my bit.

332
00:34:25,463 --> 00:34:43,911
beginning with the fundamental law of iddha-pacchiatā because that happened, this happens now because that didn't happen, this doesn't happen now because this is here, that arises because this is not here, that doesn't arise there's your fundamental plan

333
00:34:44,329 --> 00:35:12,429
so it allows an enormous creativity especially when the human will comes into it and remember human will creates and look what we've done to this planet this is human will it's human will that's doing this on top of that you've got all the laws of the universe around us you've got also the laws of culture and the laws of civilization all these things we're in the middle of

334
00:35:12,561 --> 00:35:18,630
And in the middle of that there's this little puddle with its own little internal dynamic.

335
00:35:18,650 --> 00:35:22,335
And that's us, that's our little minds and our understandings.

336
00:35:24,016 --> 00:35:30,304
And although we have contact, there's a separation.

337
00:35:30,706 --> 00:35:33,809
We all live in a little personal bubble.

338
00:35:34,262 --> 00:36:03,949
my world although none of us would disagree that this room is here we've all of us had a different experience of it even if it's very similar it's different so we live in this little bubble and this little bubble is what we're creating and if it's awful stuff then we've got through something about it and we can and if it's good stuff then we increase it and all the time we're trying to discover how it is that this bubble

339
00:36:04,199 --> 00:36:05,804
is boiling and not cool.

340
00:36:07,628 --> 00:36:13,467
Why is it that we can't be in a very peaceful state, a joyous, compassionate, loving, peaceful state?

341
00:36:18,222 --> 00:36:29,778
And remember that this individual, because of that wrong relationship to the world, whenever something happens in the world out there, will produce pleasant and unpleasant feelings.

342
00:36:30,139 --> 00:36:33,525
These pleasant and unpleasant feelings will produce a reaction.

343
00:36:34,105 --> 00:36:41,356
And the reaction is what causes all our fear, depression, anxiety, etc.

344
00:36:41,376 --> 00:36:46,744
It's not caused by the outside world, and that's the essential hope of the Buddha's message.

345
00:36:47,989 --> 00:37:14,858
that an individual can completely cure themselves of all dissatisfaction and suffering in the midst of a horrible world or beautiful world and you can do it in a very lifetime in fact you can do it in seven days if you come and join my course

346
00:37:19,849 --> 00:37:21,994
That's what the Buddha says, seven days if you really work at it.

347
00:37:23,318 --> 00:37:26,405
So, that's it really.

348
00:37:27,588 --> 00:37:31,277
Are there any immediate sort of questions that arise out of that?

